### What Model1 Improved

- Introduced the first stable benchmark for both boosting and deep learning.
- Demonstrated that engineered behavioral features are strong enough for high-performing tabular classification.
- Established the repository's shared preprocessing, evaluation, and plotting conventions.

### Model1 Limitations

- The dataset was still mostly synthetic and class-imbalanced toward humans.
- Deep learning models used synthetic sequences generated from session summaries instead of native event streams.
- Boosting clearly outperformed the DL baselines, which suggested the sequence signal was not yet rich enough.

## 3. Model2 Improved Deep Learning

### Goal

Model2 focused on improving sequence-model architecture quality without changing the broader data foundation.

### Main Changes from Model1

- residual convolutional blocks
- BatchNormalization
- larger recurrent layers
- multi-head attention in the attention model
- Transformer architecture added

### Models and Results

| Model | Accuracy | Precision | Recall | F1 Score | ROC-AUC |
| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| CNN_improved | 0.8422 | 0.8392 | 0.8422 | 0.8393 | 0.9578 |
| LSTM_improved | 0.8474 | 0.8450 | 0.8474 | 0.8459 | 0.9600 |
| CNN_LSTM_improved | 0.8407 | 0.8338 | 0.8407 | 0.8363 | 0.9614 |
| CNN_BiLSTM_improved | 0.8415 | 0.8402 | 0.8415 | 0.8403 | 0.9595 |
| CNN_Attention_LSTM_improved | 0.8459 | 0.8423 | 0.8459 | 0.8432 | 0.9625 |
| Transformer_improved | 0.8570 | 0.8573 | 0.8570 | 0.8571 | 0.9668 |

### What Model2 Improved

- Tested more modern sequence architectures than Model1.
- Added a Transformer baseline, which became the best Model2 performer.
- Improved architectural sophistication and broadened the experimental comparison space.

### Model2 Limitations

- Improvements in architecture alone did not translate into better accuracy than Model1's boosting models.
- Most improved DL models still underperformed even the original Model1 DL best case on hard classification.
- The underlying sequence data remained synthetic and inherited the same structural limitations as Model1.

## 4. Model3 High-Accuracy Deep Learning

### Goal

Model3 narrowed the search to one stronger deep-learning design rather than a broad family. It attempted to squeeze more performance out of the sequence path using a higher-capacity CNN-BiLSTM.

### Main Changes from Model2

- focused on one architecture instead of many
- higher-capacity CNN-BiLSTM
- Gaussian noise regularization
- class weighting
- label smoothing

### Model and Results

| Model | Validation Accuracy | Validation F1 | Validation ROC-AUC | Test Accuracy | Test F1 | Test ROC-AUC |
| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| HighAccuracy-CNN-BiLSTM | 0.8430 | 0.8473 | 0.9635 | 0.8526 | 0.8555 | 0.9623 |

### What Model3 Improved

- Introduced a more deliberate optimization strategy than Model2.
- Added training-time techniques aimed at better generalization.
- Produced a cleaner targeted experiment for the CNN-BiLSTM family.

### Model3 Limitations

- The final test accuracy still did not exceed Model1's best DL result in a meaningful way.
- It remained a single-model experiment, so it improved focus but reduced breadth.
- It still relied on the old synthetic sequence-generation setup rather than a more realistic input source.

## 5. Model4 Balanced Real-Human Experiment

### Goal

Model4 is the current best-organized experiment and the strongest overall pipeline in the repository. It rebuilt the workflow around a better source dataset that combines real human data with balanced bot classes.

### Dataset Context

- dataset: `data/processed/final_training_dataset_real_human_balanced_advanced.csv`
- rows: `6000`
- columns: `41`
- class distribution: `2000 human / 2000 moderate_bot / 2000 advanced_bot`
- missing values: `0`
- duplicate rows: `0`

### Main Changes from Earlier Models

- switched the main training dataset to a balanced real-human-based dataset
- kept the same advanced 41-column schema for compatibility
- created a self-contained Model4 workflow and artifact layout
- trained boosting and deep-learning models from the same validated source dataset
- generated Model4-specific sequences before deep-learning training

