### What Model4 Improved

- Delivered the best overall results in the repository.
- Improved boosting performance over Model1, with XGBoost rising from 0.8939 to 0.9225 accuracy.
- Improved all baseline DL family results over Model1 on the current balanced dataset.
- Replaced the earlier more synthetic training emphasis with a more realistic human-data foundation.
- Added a fully isolated experiment structure with dedicated reports, plots, scalers, models, and summaries.

### Model4 Limitations

- Deep-learning models still trail the best boosting models by a noticeable margin.
- Sequence data are still synthesized from session-level summaries rather than raw user-interaction timelines.
- Although the human class is now grounded in real data, moderate and advanced bot classes are still sampled from constructed data.

## 6. How the Repository Improved Over Time

### From Model1 to Model2

- The project moved from baseline DL architectures to more ambitious sequence designs.
- The main gain was architectural exploration, not final accuracy improvement.

### From Model2 to Model3

- The project moved from breadth to focus.
- Instead of many "improved" architectures, it tested one targeted high-capacity model with stronger training controls.

### From Model3 to Model4

- The biggest improvement was not only architecture but data quality and experiment design.
- Model4 introduced the balanced real-human dataset, which improved both realism and performance.
- Model4 also restored a strong combined comparison between boosting and deep learning in a clean self-contained experiment.

